  "raw_response": "{\n  \"title\": \"Three Price Examples Demonstrating Major vs Minor Swing Classification Using BOS, FVG, and Distance Criteria\",\n  \"school\": \"Smart Money Concepts (SMC)\",\n  \"asset\": \"EURUSD\",\n  \"timeframe\": \"1H\",\n  \"market_context\": \"Imperfect uptrend with choppy price action; analyst focuses on distinguishing major swing lows (origin of valid BOS) from minor swings to identify true market structure and avoid false reversals.\",\n  \"key_observation\": \"A swing point is only a major swing after a valid break of structure occurs; additional criteria—fair value gap (imbalance) and sufficient price distance (≥50% of prior impulse)—determine its strength (1–3 stars).\",\n  \"analysis_steps\": [\n    \"Step 1: The analyst states that a swing low cannot be labeled 'major' until a valid break of structure (BOS) occurs above it; only then does the origin become a major swing low.\",\n    \"Step 2: The analyst introduces the second criterion: presence of a fair value gap (FVG/imbalance) at the swing point, which strengthens its significance as a major swing.\",\n    \"Step 3: The analyst adds the third criterion: the impulsive move originating from the swing must push price at least half the distance of the prior impulse; insufficient distance invalidates it as a major swing.\",\n    \"Step 4: The analyst presents three schematic examples: (1) no BOS, no FVG, no distance → minor swing; (2) BOS + distance but no FVG → major swing (2 stars); (3) BOS + FVG + sufficient distance → major swing (3 stars).\",\n    \"",
